# Laravel Development Rules

## Architecture

- Follow Laravel conventions.
- Prefer thin controllers.
- Business logic must not live in controllers.
- Use Actions/Services for complex operations.
- Use Form Requests for validation.
- Use Policies/Gates for authorization.
- Use Events/Listeners when decoupling is useful.

## Eloquent & Queries

- Avoid N+1 queries; always check relationships before querying.
- Prefer eager loading.
- Do not use `Model::all()` on large tables.
- Use pagination for lists.
- Use chunk/cursor for batch processing.
- Avoid loading unnecessary columns.

Bad:

```php
User::all();

foreach ($users as $user) {
    echo $user->profile->name;
}

$orders = Order::get();
foreach ($orders as $order) {
    $order->items;
}
```

Good:

```php
$users = User::with('profile')->paginate();

User::select(['id', 'name'])->get();

Order::with('items')->get();

Model::chunk(500, function ($items) {
    // ...
});

Model::cursor();
```

## Database

- Always consider indexes when filtering, sorting, or joining frequently.
- Avoid unnecessary queries, duplicated queries, and unnecessary joins.
- Prefer query builder for complex queries.
- Avoid raw SQL unless necessary.
- Analyze slow queries.

## Performance

- Use cache for expensive queries, external API calls, and computed values (`Cache::remember()`).
- Use queues for heavy operations: emails, imports, exports, notifications, integrations.
- Avoid blocking requests.
- Consider Redis for cache and queues.

## Security

- Never use `$request->all()` for persistence.
- Use validated data.
- Protect mass assignment.
- Validate uploads.
- Apply authorization rules.

## API

- Keep API responses consistent.
- Use Laravel Resources.
- Avoid exposing database models directly.
- Use proper HTTP status codes.
- Minimize payload size; avoid unnecessary relationships.
- Paginate large responses.

## Code Quality

- Follow PSR-12.
- Keep methods small.
- Prefer dependency injection.
- Write readable code over clever code.

## Before changing code

- Understand existing architecture.
- Reuse existing patterns.
- Avoid introducing unnecessary dependencies.
